{"parse":{"title":"Hafsa bint Sirin","pageid":54346463,"revid":795552780,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Hafsa bint Sirin</b> (? - 101/719 c.e.)<sup id=\"cite_ref-CookHaider2013_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CookHaider2013-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> was a woman and an early scholar of Islam.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hasyim2006_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hasyim2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> She has been called one of the \"pioneers in the history of female asceticism in Island\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sayeed2013-70_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sayeed2013-70-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>She lived in <a href=\"/wiki/Basra\" title=\"Basra\">Basra</a>, taught numerous students, was known for her piety and knowledge and practical and legal aspects of Islamic traditions, and has been credited with seventeen traditions. <sup id=\"cite_ref-Sayeed2013-73_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sayeed2013-73-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>She was a sister of <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Sirin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Muhammad ibn Sirin\">Muhammad ibn Sirin</a>, known for dream interpretation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Helminski2003_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Helminski2003-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hafsa_bint_Sirin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Umm_al-Darda\" title=\"Umm al-Darda\">Umm al-Darda</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hafsa_bint_Sirin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Mu\u1e25ammad ibn al-\u1e24usayn Sulam\u012b (1999). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=D1rYAAAAMAAJ\"><i>Dhikr An-Niswa Al-Muta\u02bfabbid\u0101t A\u1e63-S\u016bfiyy\u0101t</i></a>. Fons Vitae. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-887752-06-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-887752-06-0\">978-1-887752-06-0</a>,</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Dhikr+An-Niswa+Al-Muta%CA%BFabbid%C4%81t+A%E1%B9%A3-S%C5%ABfiyy%C4%81t&amp;rft.pub=Fons+Vitae&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-887752-06-0&amp;rft.au=Mu%E1%B8%A5ammad+ibn+al-%E1%B8%A4usayn+Sulam%C4%AB&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DD1rYAAAAMAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHafsa+bint+Sirin\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> has a chapter dedicated to Hafsa bint Sirin (Chapter XXI, p.122-).</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hafsa_bint_Sirin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-CookHaider2013-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-CookHaider2013_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Michael Cook; Najam Haider; Intisar Rabb; Asma Sayeed (8 January 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=hoLQdb1mlncC&amp;pg=PA96\"><i>Law and Tradition in Classical Islamic T